<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="239" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,151,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Araujo Junior" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Araujo Junior" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[276,481,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Episcepsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fumata" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[276,481,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">Episcepsis fumata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[490,620,151,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[490,620,151,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
was described from two males. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rothschild" box="[994,1199,151,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" refString="Rothschild, W. (1912) New Syntomidae. Novitates Zoologicae, 19 (2), 151 - 186." type="journal article" year="1912">Rothschild (1912)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that both already had the wings considerably worn by the time they were described. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hampson" box="[998,1187,188,212]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1914) Catalogue of the Lepidoptera Phalaenae in the British Museum, Supplement. vol. I. Catalogue of the Amatidae and Arctiadae (Nolinae and Lithosianae) in the collection of the British Museum. Printed by the order of the Trustees of the British Museum, London, 858 pp." type="book" year="1914">Hampson (1914)</bibRefCitation>
thought the specimen from La Unión was a female, and designated the other, from Pambilar, 
<collectingCountry box="[958,1053,223,248]" name="Ecuador" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, as the 
<typeStatus box="[1138,1243,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">lectotype</typeStatus>
, even though the Peruvian specimen held a handwritten 
<typeStatus box="[588,636,261,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">type</typeStatus>
label with Rothschild's handwrinting. Nevertheless, Hampson's (1914) 
<typeStatus box="[151,254,295,320]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">lectotype</typeStatus>
designation is valid.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">
This species is close to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Druce, 1897)" authorityName="Druce" authorityYear="1897" baseAuthorityName="Druce" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[490,829,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Episcepsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moloneyi">
<emphasis box="[490,642,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">E. moloneyi</emphasis>
(Druce, 1897)
</taxonomicName>
(described from 
<collectingRegion box="[1037,1109,332,357]" country="Belize" name="Belize" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">
<collectingCountry box="[1037,1109,332,357]" name="Belize" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">Belize</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
and figured in the original description, pl. 72, fig. 16; by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hampson" box="[491,672,368,392]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1898) Catalogue of the Lepidoptera Phalaenae in the British Museum, vol. I: Catalogue of the Syntomidae in the collection of the British Museum. Printed by the order of the Trustees of the British Museum, London, xxi + 559 pp., foldout phylogeny chart, 285 figs., pls. 1 - 17." type="book chapter" year="1898">Hampson, 1898</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 197; and by Draudt, 1915, pl. 20, row d) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Schaus, 1910" authorityName="Schaus" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Episcepsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sixola">
<emphasis box="[1237,1335,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">E. sixola</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Schaus" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" refString="Schaus, W. (1910) Descriptions of new Heterocera from Costa Rica. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 8 (6), 189 - 211. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222931008692838" type="journal article" year="1910">Schaus, 1910</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(described from 
<collectingCountry box="[398,523,404,429]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, figured in 
<bibRefCitation author="Hampson" box="[649,829,404,428]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" refString="Hampson, G. F. (1914) Catalogue of the Lepidoptera Phalaenae in the British Museum, Supplement. vol. I. Catalogue of the Amatidae and Arctiadae (Nolinae and Lithosianae) in the collection of the British Museum. Printed by the order of the Trustees of the British Museum, London, 858 pp." type="book" year="1914">Hampson, 1914</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 13, fig. 5 and Draudt, 1915: pl. 28, row k), both of which seem to belong to a monophyletic concept of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1877" box="[754,872,440,463]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Episcepsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[754,872,440,463]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">Episcepsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, given the similarities observed in male genitalia (pers. obs.).These species share with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Araujo Junior" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Araujo Junior" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[568,677,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Episcepsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fumata" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[568,677,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">E. fumata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[684,813,476,501]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[684,813,476,501]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
the red spots on tegulae, and the sparse white scales on proximal and medial areas of hindwings.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Araujo Junior" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Araujo Junior" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[199,408,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Episcepsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fumata" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[199,408,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">Episcepsis fumata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[420,553,548,573]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[420,553,548,573]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schaus" authorityYear="1910" box="[904,1008,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Episcepsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sixola">
<emphasis box="[904,1008,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">E. sixola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Druce" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[1073,1212,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Episcepsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moloneyi">
<emphasis box="[1073,1212,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">E. moloneyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of iridescent scales (present in both of the latter), and by the many white spots on various parts of the body. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pinheiro &amp; Araujo Junior" authorityYear="2017" pageId="8" pageNumber="239" rank="subSpecies" status="comb. nov." subSpecies="fumata">
Moreover, 
<emphasis box="[151,260,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">E. fumata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[266,394,620,645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[266,394,620,645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="239">comb. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
